We are taking a look back at some of the amazing times we've had this past school year!

Today we look back at the AP Chill Zone!

The AP Chill Zone was established by the counseling center for a place to come relax and make new friends during activity period. Students did various activities throughout the year such as painting pumpkins, building gingerbread houses, and making valentines cards for sick children in the hospital.

Check out this video feature on the various chill zones from earlier this year!

When the COVID-19 shutdown began, Mr. Slauson's students were just about finished building ukuleles in their Computer Integrated Manufacturing class. The students made these instruments while learning about CNC machining, robotics, laser engraving and CAD design.

Mr. Slauson was able to return the ukuleles to the students so they could sand and finish them completely!

Here are a few pictures of these beautiful instruments! Great work!

Due to Governor Cuomo’s Executive Order, the Skaneateles Central School District Campus remains closed to the public.

In addition, we have major ongoing projects throughout our campus associated with Project 2021.

For safety reasons, we ask that everyone please refrain from using any walkways, fields, or other areas of the campus. We will be beginning some major construction at the Middle School and want to make the public aware that you may hear some loud noises in the coming weeks associated with the demolition of the gymnasium.

If you have any questions or concerns, please contact Elaine MacLachlan at emaclach@skanschools.org.

Thank You!

post_text:
We are so fortunate to have the wonderful staff that we have here in Skaneateles!

Emily Cullen and her staff have been working tirelessly throughout the COVID-19 pandemic to ensure the nutritional needs of our community are met on a daily basis.

Over 2,100 meals are prepared and delivered per week to those in need.

By June 29, roughly 27,000 meals will have been delivered since the closure of our school buildings.

We could not be more grateful to all of the staff involved in the preparation and delivery of this much needed service that you have masterfully provided.

Thank you so much for all that you do!

CELEBRATING OUR GRADUATES! Class of 2020 Online Auction!

Senior parents and businesses have generously donated beautiful baskets and unique items to help raise money to support upcoming celebrations for the Class of 2020! This auction was originally scheduled for March 13th at the Senior Pasta Dinner but was cancelled due to Covid-19. The auction will now be hosted on-line and will run from June 1st - June 5th. Proceeds from the auction will be used for events and activities to celebrate our Seniors during the month of June and beyond. The Senior Ball is currently rescheduled for early August and funds from the auction will be contributed to the Ball to help make the event a night to remember.

Please click the link below to view the auction items and bid. We will arrange for payment and deliver/pick-up of items once bidding is complete.
https://www.32auctions.com/organizations/64071

Thank you for your support!

shared_text:
Brian Franco shared a post to the group: Skaneateles K-12 Music.
May 26 at 9:51 AM ·

"Humanism" by Jon Batiste, as performed by members of the Skaneateles Jazz Band (and some staff!) during quarantine.

Brian Franco
May 26 at 8:18 AM ·

Members of the Skaneateles High School Jazz Band play from home, together:

"Humanism"
-Jon Batiste arr. Paul Murtha

I wanted to try a virtual performance, so I reached out to the members of my jazz band and asked if they'd be interested. This was a totally optional assignment, and it was great to put together.

Filmed on their individual phones over the course of a week, compiled, edited and mixed by me.

This in no way replicates a live performance, but was fun to work on. Special thanks to Sarah Midgley-Scuderi for covering the tenor 2 part!

Qualified voters on the most recent years’ poll lists will be automatically sent an absentee ballot. Anyone who meets the definition of a “qualified voter,” but does not believe he/she will be on the School District’s poll list, which contains the names of residents who voted in recent years’ elections, please contact the District Clerk, Karen Dunphy, by email at kdunphy@skanschools.org as soon as possible to ensure timely receipt of an absentee ballot for the 2020 annual meeting/election.

The United States Postal Service estimates delivery for first class mail to be two to five days. Please consider this information when mailing back your ballot, as all ballots need to be received at the District Office by 5:00 pm June 9, 2020.

On Friday May 15th, Skaneateles CSD Faculty and Staff are going to “Light the Night” to honor the class of 2020!

At approximately 8:20 pm (20:20 military time) the Arthur W. Hyatt stadium lights will go on for 20 minutes as a sign of support for our students.

We are inviting our Seniors to join us in a vehicle parade that will pass by the turf field. The parade route will start at the MS entrance and follow the driveway behind the building, pass by the field, then exit the HS parking lot onto Elizabeth Street.

We hope to see all of the seniors there!

post_text:
SENIOR CLASS OF 2020!
On Friday May 15th, Skaneateles CSD Faculty and Staff are going to “Light the Night” to honor the class of 2020. At approximately 8:20 pm (20:20 military time) the Arthur W. Hyatt stadium lights will go on for 20 minutes as a sign of support for our students. We are inviting our Seniors to join us in a vehicle parade that will pass by the turf field. The parade route will start at the MS entrance and follow the driveway behind the building, pass by the field, then exit the HS parking lot onto Elizabeth Street.
For your safety, this event is a vehicle event only.

1. You must stay in your care.
2. You must maintain a 5-10 mile/hr speed limit.
3. No parking is allowed.
4. Walkers will be turned way.
5. Law enforcement will be present to provide support.

A video will be published after the event to share with the families of these students, as well as with the community.

post_text: Congratulations to Keady Azzam and Zachary LaComb! Both of these outstanding students were selected to receive the 2020 National Junior Honor Society, Outstanding Achievement Awards! Recognizing the need to help middle level students jump-start their quest toward higher education, the National Junior Honor Society recognizes 500 NJHS students nationwide with a scholarship, and given their hard work and dedication at the Middle School, Keady and Zachary deserve this honor! Congratulations! 🤩🤩

post_text:
Good Morning!

Construction on Project 2021 is continuing throughout the District and our contractors are making great progress. For your safety and the safety of the construction workers and staff, we kindly ask that you do not use the paths or areas that are currently blocked off with construction signs, fencing and/or tape. The contractors are using heavy equipment and are working with electrical lines in these areas. These areas will remain closed to the public until construction is complete. Thank you for your cooperation in this matter.

Our Project 2021 web page will be up and running very soon. This page will have timelines, pictures, updates and frequently asked questions. In the meantime, should you have any questions, please contact Elaine MacLachlan at emaclach@skanschools.org.

Thank you and have a wonderful day!

This website will continue to be updated during the Covid-19 shutdown.

We miss you all so much and hope to hear from you!

Dear Families,

Our school is hosting a Virtual Scholastic Book Fair from April 15th through April 28th.
The Virtual Fair is a fantastic way to get books in the hands of your students now to keep them reading at home.
• All purchases benefit our school and earn rewards
• Shop Book Fair exclusives, best-sellers, skill-builders and more
• Orders ship direct to home
• Book-only orders over $25* receive FREE shipping
• Over 6,000 items to choose from through the Scholastic Store Online

post_text:
THANK YOU to our amazing School Lunch Director, Emily Cullen, her phenomenal staff, the bus drivers delivering meals, and our custodial staff for keeping us all clean and safe! We thank them all for their commitment and hard work.

With the support of the Skaneateles Ecumenical Food Pantry and Skaneateles Outreach, we are able to extend our table to the entire community.

Breakfast and lunch are available to any family, regardless of income. Community members do NOT need to have children in the school system, and do not need submit any financial paperwork. These are unsettling times, and the SCSD, along with the generous support of our community, will be extending our table to all of our families.

We ask that anyone who would like to receive meals, please contact Emily Cullen at ecullen@skanschools.org or leave her a message at 315-291-2248.

Donations can still be made via this link:
https://www.townofskaneateles.com/covid-19/outreach-covid-19-relief-fund/

LEGAL NOTICE
Transportation to Private Schools

Parents and guardians of resident pupils in the Skaneateles School District are reminded that requests for transportation to private schools for the 2020-21 school year must be filed with the District by April 15, 2020.

Requests are to be submitted in writing and must include legal name of the child, the address of residence, the child's date of birth, grade level and the name and address of the school that the child plans to attend. The parent or guardian’s full name and telephone number should also be included.

All written transportation requests or questions, should be mailed to Dr. Jeffrey Bryant, Interim Superintendent of Schools in the Skaneateles Central School District, 45 East Elizabeth Street, Skaneateles, NY 13152.

Dear SCSD Families:

The Board of Education will meet tomorrow for its regularly scheduled meeting at 7:00 pm. However, due to social distancing requirements, the Board will be meeting via an online ZOOM meeting platform. Only Board Members will have access to attend the ZOOM meeting, but it will be live streamed using Ensemble, which will allow the public to view the meeting in real time. Please go to the Skaneateles Schools website for information on how view the meeting, or click on this link below:

http://www.skanschools.org/districtpage.cfm?pageid=2807

In the absence of an in-person Public Comment section, the Board of Education asks that all comments be submitted before the meeting. The Board will try to address the issues raised, and will follow up with public responses in writing if needed. Please send all comments and questions to the District Clerk at kdunphy@skanschools.org

Thank you.
Sincerely,
The Board of Education

Chromebooks will be available for pick up tomorrow (Friday, March 20 th) from 9 am - 1 pm for students in grades 3-12.

State Street: 9 am - 1 pm Pick Up at the back of the school, by the baseball field.
Middle School 9 am - 1 pm Pick Up at the MS Main entrance
High School 9 am - 1 pm Pick Up at the HS Main entrance

If you are not able to pick up during this window, please contact your building principal.

If you have a laptop, iPad, or Chromebook at home already, where your child can access the internet, you may not need to pick up a Chromebook from your child's school. We will have a Chromebook available for every student who needs one, but we ask that if you have enough technology at home, to not pick up an extra device.

For families who do not have internet access at home, please call the district office so that we can work on securing internet access with you. Please call Karen Dunphy at 315-291-2221 or send an email to kdunphy@skanschools.org as soon as possible.

More information is available on our website at www.skanschools.org

post_text:
Materials are now available for anyone wishing to run for a Board of Education seat this May 19th. Two seats will be open this year. Contact the District Clerk, Karen Dunphy for more information.
kdunphy@skanschools.org

Petitions must be filed with the District Clerk no later than April 20, 2019 at 5:00 p.m. in the District Office located at 45 East Elizabeth Street, Skaneateles, New York. A valid petition must contain at least 25 signatures of district residents eligible to vote in the district election. An eligible voter must be a citizen of the United States, be at least 18 years old, and be a resident of the Skaneateles School district for at least 30 days prior to the day of the vote (and who is not otherwise prohibited from voting under the provisions of section 5-106 of the Election Law).

During this challenging time, so many people are working diligently and with compassion so that those in need are cared for. Our School Lunch Director, Emily Cullen, and her staff, have been working with the Skaneateles Outreach Office, and the Skaneateles Ecumenical Food Pantry, to set up systems that ensure all families in need will be able to receive meals for their children.

Anyone needing assistance in the community can call either of these organizations:

Skaneateles Outreach (Jacque McConnaghy) 315-685-0427 or 315-283-4281
Skaneateles Ecumenical Food Pantry (Judy Gelston) 315-685-3512

Finally, if you would like to help fund the efforts on behalf of Skaneateles Outreach and the Food Pantry, you can visit the website below and click on the DONATE button to make a credit card donation.

https://www.townofskaneateles.com/covid-19/outreach-covid-19-relief-fund/

For more information, and other ways to donate, please visit our website.

We had a great turnout for tonight's showing of Screenagers NEXT CHAPTER: Uncovering Skills for Stress Resilience!

The documentary discusses the many anxieties our children face in the digital age and what we can do to help them succeed.

Following the screening Dr. Kevin Antshel, Director of Clinical Training at Syracuse University answered questions and had a discussion elaborating on the topics discussed in the film.

We would like to give a huge thank you to the Skaneateles PTC for sponsoring this important event!

In February, we focus on our Waterman Words, COMPASSION and KINDNESS. This year, Waterman is showing their compassion to a local, nonprofit organization called Griffin’s Guardians. Griffin’s Guardians helps families in CNY that are battling pediatric cancer. We have 2 days left to contribute to our Change for Hope Campaign. We have almost met our goal, but we need a little more help. If you are able, please send in change to donate. Thank you for showing compassion by supporting this great cause!

The Chill Zones focus on de-stressing and relaxing with friends which are beneficial to both the mental and physical health and wellness of students!

Students of all grade levels are encouraged to take advantage of these wonderful events!

post_text:
The Skaneateles Education Foundation has awarded Jessica Sawchuk in the Art Department a grant to take twenty students to The Ink Shop in Ithaca, NY!

Students will be creating stencil monoprints, a unique and dynamic form of printmaking, and working side by side with artists in the studio.

This opportunity gives each student the chance to work with new materials, approach the creative process from a different perspective and talk with working artists who run this amazing studio!

We would like to give a huge thank you to the Skaneateles Education Foundation for this generous grant!

post_text:
Monday, March 9th - Join the High School PTC in the screening of the documentary film, SCREENAGERS. All parents are encouraged to attend this free event.

Skaneateles High School Auditorium, 6:00 pm. After the movie, Dr. Kevin Antshel will moderate a discussion.

About the Film: Filmmaker and physician Dr. Delaney Ruston takes the conversation around screens and teens to the next level with Screenagers NEXT CHAPTER: Uncovering Skills for Stress Resilience—a film that examines the science behind teen’s emotional challenges, the interplay of social media, and most importantly, what can be done in our schools and homes to help them build crucial skills to navigate stress, anxiety, and depression in our digital age.
